		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Better call the crowd: using crowdsourcing to shape the notation of domain-specific languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MarcoBrambilla.html">Marco Brambilla</a>, <a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a>, <a href="../profile/JavierLuisCánovasIzquierdo.html">Javier Luis Cánovas Izquierdo</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreaMauri.html">Andrea Mauri</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136033">10.1145/3136014.3136033</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagM">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s main aim is improving usability/acceptance of DSML notations by involving end-users via crowdsourcing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It directly concerns the design of a language’s notation (concrete syntax) informed by user feedback.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> Crowdsourcing implies empirical collection and analysis of user preferences over notational alternatives.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The setting is domain-specific modeling languages whose notations are being designed.
</li></ul></li></ul>
